    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Long Battle Over Gay Troops</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>American Legion National Commander Alan G Lance Sr letter on July 27 editorial opposes lifting ban on openly homosexual soldiers; calls for swift enforcement on anti-harassment rules</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Pentagon's Anti-Gay Policies'' (editorial, July 27):</p>
        <p>The ban on homosexuals serving openly in the military was developed by military leaders who experienced firsthand the damage to unit cohesion caused by the presence of openly gay troops. Lifting the ban, which you call for, is not the answer because it would damage unit cohesion.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Pentagon's Anti-Gay Policies'' (editorial, July 27):</p>
        <p>The ban on homosexuals serving openly in the military was developed by military leaders who experienced firsthand the damage to unit cohesion caused by the presence of openly gay troops. Lifting the ban, which you call for, is not the answer because it would damage unit cohesion.</p>
        <p>When it comes to fighting and winning battles, readiness trumps any political agenda. The answer to the harassment problem is swift enforcement of the Uniform Code of Military Justice so that harassment of any kind is punished and deterred.  ALAN G. LANCE SR.  National Commander  The American Legion  Washington, July 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
